It seems all sides in the country are expecting the election to happen, with the old guard hoping to use to reestablish their normal power structures and the opposition planning to use low turnout to increase pressure on the regime. It is possible the situation will spiral out of control again or that an opposition figure will win, but it seems overwhelmingly likely that Le Pouvoir will stay in power.

FLN have won 3 of the last 4 elections and given the current regime's control on the upcoming election (Interior Ministry controlling Electoral Commission) this outcome seems the most likely outcome by some margin.

Lets examine first the reasons that could result in the election not being held: - Increase of mass protests. The protestors have decreased since the Bouteflika resignation, however, they keep taking the streets every week, and they show themselves committed with a real change, and against the 12 December elections. So, i assign a 20% chance of the election being cancelled due to the protests. This would be higher if in the next weeks we see an increase of violence, but for the moment the protestors have been pacific. -Logistic problems. The last elections were scheduled in july, but they were cancelled because no candidate was presented (although it is said that the real reason was the lack of logistic capability to organise the election). This time, however, the army chief Gaid Salah has been very clear about his intention to hold the election, and the Algerian Press Service has announced 137 candidate petitions so i think there is no more than a 5% chance. -Elite breakdown. The political elite in Algeria is not completely united. Although Gaid Salah is the visible face, there is some factions that are not very happy to hold the election. However, they know now is not the best moment to start a conflict between themselves, so i think there is a 3% chance for the internal power struggle to happen.
